<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU New Move Against Polluting Emission From Trucks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- New diesel-engined trucks will
have to reduce polluting exhaust fumes and particulate emissions
by a further 30 percent by 2000 as the European Union made a new
move to improve air quality.
</P>
<P>
The move, according to today's issue of the European Report
journal, was within the framework of the union's auto-oil air
quality program to further reduce air pollution caused by motor
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, European Union's executive, set in a
proposal new emission limits for trucks and diesel engines,
requirements for new gas-powered trucks and truck engines as well
as a substantial modification of test methods for vehicle type
approval.
</P>
<P>
The proposal seeks to amend requirements on diesel emissions by
trucks first imposed in 1988 and most recently amended in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The proposed measures are part of the European Community system
of type approval of truck engines and must be applied in the case
of all new type approvals granted by national authorities.
</P>
<P>
It introduces new requirements concerning polluting emissions
by engines fuelled by natural gas and liquefied petroleum gas.
</P>
<P>
The new limits will apply to emissions of carbon monoxide,
unburnt hydrocarbons, nitrogen oxides, particulates, and to
exhaust smoke opacity as well as to methane emissions.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that it would unveil another set of
proposals in 1999 to establish stricter limit values which are
neutral as concerns the fuel and techniques used.
</P>
<P>
The new set of limit values will apply as of 2005 at the
conclusion of a second auto-oil program and will serve as the
basis for a European tax incentive plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
