<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Demands Reports on U.S. School Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today ordered law enforcement and education officials to produce
annual reports on violence in U.S. schools.
</P>
<P>
"We know more about the overall patterns of car theft in
America than we do about the harm that comes to our children at
school," Clinton said in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's address came a week after three girls were gunned
down by a 14-year-old schoolmate in a Kentucky school.
</P>
<P>
"We simply cannot educate our children -- and they cannot learn
and live up to their full potential -- when violence and drugs
threaten their safety in schools," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "High school seniors are more likely to take weapons
to school than to take calculus in school. This is unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Offering his proposal in memory of the three girls, Jessica
James, Kayce Steger and Nicole Hadley, Clinton said, "Now the rest
of us must do everything in our power to prevent such things from
happening again."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "Youth violence represents an insistent, angry
wake-up call to every parent, every teacher, every religious
leader, every student." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
