<HEADLINE> Albright, Arafat Hold "Constructive" Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Palestinian Authority Chairman Yasser
Arafat held talks here today on the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The three-hour talks were "constructive", Albright and Arafat
agreed at a joint press conference following the talks at the
mission of the United States of America in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Albright announced that she would meet separately again with
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Europe
next week.
</P>
<P>
"They have some work to do and some decisions to make before we
have those meetings somewhere in western Europe upon my return
from Africa next week," she said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Albright met with Netanyahu in Paris. They were said
to have had three-hour "useful talks".
</P>
<P>
During today's talks which she described as "useful and
constructive", Albright and Arafat went over in some detail a
four-part agenda, and spent some time discussing various aspects.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told reporters that his talks with Albright were
"important and constructive".
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace is "important not only for Palestinians and
Israelis, but also for the entire world," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
