<HEADLINE> Transparency Urged for Zimbabwe's Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The 5,000 delegates to
Zimbabwe's ruling Zanu (PF)'s annual national conference which
ended today have called on the government to ensure transparency
and fairness in redistribution of land acquired from the white
commercial farmers.
</P>
<P>
A resolution adopted at the end of the two-day conference
commended the government for taking bold steps to resolve the
land issue, 17 years after the attainment of Zimbabwe's
independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to acquire about 1,500 farms or five
million hectares for resettlement and commercial farming for the
landless indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
The conference also urged the government to ensure the success
of the indigenization program by formulating comprehensive
policies which would lead to increased participation in all
sectors of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The delegates called for a water development policy to ensure
equitable access of the majority of the people and encourage the
establishment of irrigations schemes in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
