<HEADLINE> Nigeria Holds State Assembly Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian military
government's transition to civil rule program took another major
step today, with the holding of the state assembly elections.
</P>
<P>
More than 55,700,000 registered voters were expected to go out
to vote, but investigations show that the turnout was
impressively low.
</P>
<P>
At a polling station in Lagos, only less than 20 ballots were
cast by the time the poll ended at 3:00 p.m., whereas more than
700 voters were registered there.
</P>
<P>
The city, however, has been quite calm and quiet, as the
authority has imposed a traffic restriction.
</P>
<P>
The country's five political parties have fielded a total of
about 4,900 candidates for the 989 state legislative seats
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
In the local council election held in March, the United
Nigeria Congress Party (UNCP) sealed an overwhelming victory,
bagging more than 300 of the 770 local council chairmanship
seats. The Democratic Party of Nigeria came the second with about
130 seats.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have forecast that the UNCP is likely to maintain its
majority in today's elections.
</P>
<P>
According to the amended transition program, the state
assembly election will be followed by the national congress
election in April next and a presidential election in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
