<HEADLINE> Scarcity Doubles S. Leone's Rice Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone has been hit by
a scarcity of rice forcing the price of a 110 pound bag from 20
and 25 dollars to 35 and 40 dollars today.
</P>
<P>
The steep rise sent panic among consumers in the capital as
hundreds visit shops after being told that all rice stock had
been sold out.
</P>
<P>
Consumers blamed "unpatriotic rice sellers" mainly Lebanese of
" hoarding rice" in anticipation of a continued sanction imposed
on the country since the coup.
</P>
<P>
One Lebanese merchant reacting to charges of hoarding said "we
cannot do this as we have stood behind the Sierra Leone people
since the coup."
</P>
<P>
"We would be endangering our own security to create hardship
on the people," he added.
</P>
<P>
Trade Minister Eldred Collins told Xinhua, "we wonder over the
reason for this shortage. It is likely to undermine the people's
confidence on us, so we won't take things lightly if we find out
that our detractors are using rice as a political weapon to
derail the government."
</P>
<P>
Thousands of bags of rice are usually allocated to the Sierra
Leone military and its ally, the people 's Army each month at a
nominal rate of one dollar a bag.
</P>
<P>
The last major consignment of rice was brought into the
country in August by a Lebanese merchant.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone imports most of its rice, the country's staple
food from China, Pakistan and Burma at an annual cost of
30,000,000 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of crates of soft drinks including Coke,
Fanta, Pepsi and Vimto have flooded the Sierra Leone market
ending about three months of scarcity.
</P>
<P>
Customs officlals said they believed the consignment has been
brought in by civilian traders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
