<HEADLINE> Zambians Urged to Fight Against Cultural Heritage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official
called here today for collective efforts against illegal trade of
cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Minister Amussa Mwanamwambwa told reporters that the
illicit trade of cultural heritage which has become a global
problem should be combated through collective efforts and
increased enforcement capacities supported by severe penalties.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made by Mwanamwambwa when he handed over to
Livingstone Museum seven objects that were stolen in 1989 and
recovered in Brussel with the help of the International Council
of Museums.
</P>
<P>
The tourism minister pointed out that the scourge of illicit
trade in cultural heritage has continued to rob Zambia and the
whole of Africa of much of its invaluable heritage.
</P>
<P>
He added that a lot of Zambia's cultural patrimony has found
its way to Europe through the clandestine trade promoted by some
people in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mwanamwambwa urged the directors in charge of national museums
to adopt effective measures to protect the country's cultural
heritage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
