<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Renews Debt Relief Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 6 (Xinhua) -- President Benjamin Mkapa
has renewed his appeal for debt relief to Tanzania, saying the
country's debt is at an "unburably high" level.
</P>
<P>
Talking to representatives of donor countries and agencies at
the State House in Dar es Salaam today, Mkapa said the government
is at present spending 37 percent of its revenue in debt
repayment.
</P>
<P>
Heavy debt has made Tanzania short of fund in developing
health and education undertakings, he said.
</P>
<P>
During today's informal talks with some 30 representatives
ahead of the Consultative Group Meeting (CGM) on Tanzania
schedule for next Wednesday, Mkapa said that the debt service
ration is well above the recommended rate between 15 and 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
The amount of money used by the government for debt repayment
per capita stands at 11.5 US Dollars annually, while the spending
on health and education is only two US Dollars, the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's external debt by October 31 had reached 8.0881
billion US dollars, according to the central Bank of Tanzania
(BOT).
</P>
<P>
CGM is a forum at which major donor countries and institutions
collectively meet individual developing countries to review
donor-funded projects and agree on future terms of cooperation.
The forum is normally held in Paris.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the State House noted that "the
decision by the donors to come to Dar es Salaam rather than
summon Tanzania representatives to Paris, is a gesture of
confidence in the Tanzanian government in the implementation of
political, economic and social services," 
</P>
</TEXT>
