<HEADLINE> Next Government to Continue Graft Fight: Moi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today said that he would "continue with the war against graft
and other forms of corruption that make good business practice
difficult".
</P>
<P>
Speaking here at a fund-raising luncheon organized by the
ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU), Moi noted that the
next KANU government would give priority to elimination of
corruption to make the country more caring and united.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that he would persistently seek peace to create
a conducive environment for the business community in the East
African country.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan President urged the business community to support
KANU during the critical campaign for the December 29 General
Election and the transition into next century.
</P>
<P>
The lunch which was attended by members of business community
raised some 100.75 million Kenyan Shillings (about 1.6 million
U.S. Dollars) for the KANU election fund.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Daily Nation reported on Friday that 35
people given red invitation cards for the top table were expected
to contribute up to five million Shillings (about 80,000
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Moi said that he would approach young executives both men and
women to organize such fund-raising events in all major towns in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Charity Ngilu, leading opposition presidential candidate for
Social Democratic Party, called for a demonstration against the
lunch, saying that the event was a sign of rampant corruption in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Nairobi residents today ignored the call and only some two
hundred Ngilu supporters showed up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
