<HEADLINE> Frank Nobilo Wins Hong Kong Open Golf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's Frank Nobilo
won the 350,000 U.S. dollars Hong Kong Open golf tournament on
Sunday to record the first back-to-back success in his career.
</P>
<P>
Nobilo, winner of the Mexico Open two weeks ago, ran away from
the pack with a closing birdie on the 18th hole to end at a
three-under-par 68 in the final round. He won the four-round,
72-hole event with a total of 17-under 267, five strokes clear of
runner-up Kang Wook-soon from South Korea, the leading player on
last year's Asian PGA tour.
</P>
<P>
Nobilo took the 58,345 U.S. dollars top prize.
</P>
<P>
American Tim Straub recorded a total of 274, 10 under par, in
the first international golf tournament after Hong Kong's handover
on July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Lianwei, China's top professional golfer, closed his race
with a collection of 275, nine under par, to tie with Chinese
Taipei's Lin Keng-chi for the fourth place.
</P>
<P>
Nobilo started poorly with two bogeys in the first three holes
but he soon showed his caliber as the world's 22nd-ranked
player. He started a winning advance with an eagle at the ninth
hole and four birdies at the 10th, 12th, 14th and final holes.
</P>
<P>
"When I dropped shots early on it opened up the whole field,"
said Nobilo. "I knew he (Kang) was up level with me and it was
not much fun for a while.
</P>
<P>
"It took me a long time to find my rhythm," he said. "After
that, I felt great again, just like the past three days.
</P>
<P>
"That's the first time I have backed up one tournament win with
another and it feels great," Nobilo said.
</P>
<P>
Nobilo praised Asian players for their improvement. "Asian
players did very well this week, such as Kang and Lin they scored
a 66, and a 67, and of course Zhang Lianwei shooting a 9 under,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang admitted that he was nervous at the start of the final
round Sunday. "But after two bogeys at the two opening holes, I
came to see that there's little chance for me to win. That helped
to be relaxed and do better in the later stage," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am happy with my performance. It was a good week for me,"
added Zhang, who is to compete in the Omega PGA Championships
later next week in Hong Kong and another event in the Philippines
for the year.
</P>
<P>
The spectators at the Hong Kong Golf Club ignored the weather
which switched from rain to wind time to time. Organizers
registered a crowd of 8,000, a record for the Hong Kong Open
history.
</P>
<P>
"It's an energetic crowd, it's good for golf," said Nobilo at
the awarding ceremony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
