<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Reaches 47 in Russian Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian rescuers digging through
rubble have found the remains of 47 people killed when a military
cargo plane crashed Saturday morning into an apartment building
after takeoff in the Siberian city of Irkutsk.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the victims of the 23 people aboard the plane,
the crash caused a fire in several buildings which killed two
children in an orphanage and at least 22 local residents,
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The death toll was expected to rise as the rescue work went on,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The crash destroyed a 64-apartment housing some 200 people and
damaged other three apartment buildings and an orphanage and a
school, the reports added.
</P>
<P>
About 450 people have been evacuated from the area and the
rescue workers were continuing to search the debris and nearby
homes.
</P>
<P>
The Antonov-124 was reportedly carrying two Sukhoi-27 fighter
planes for export to Vietnam but plunged to the ground seconds
after taking off in Irkutsk.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the aircraft was 10 seconds into its flight
after taking off when its two left engines failed at an altitude
of about 70 meters. It slammed in to a residential area soon after
its take-off.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin has ordered Prime Minister Vikto
Chernomyridin to go to the scene and head up the investigation
into the accident.
</P>
<P>
The city also experienced a crash in 1994, in which all 125
people on aboard a Russian Tupolev-154 plane were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
