<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Urges Kaunda to Help Zambia Move Forward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba, who is on a one-day working visit in Zimbabwe, today
expressed his hope that Zambia's former president Kenneth Kaunda
could make contribution to the resolution of Zambia's political
problems and help the country move forward.
</P>
<P>
When meeting the press soon after his one and half hours'
private talks with Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, Chiluba
said he hoped that one day Kaunda would realize the need to help
the country to move forward, according to a report from the
Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Kaunda, leader of Zambia's main
opposition United National Independence Party (UNIP), has been
seeking asylum in Harare after an abortive military coup in
October to overthrow the government led by Chiluba's ruling
Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD).
</P>
<P>
Chiluba is touring the world lobbying for loans to push
forward dialogue between the MMD government and the opposition so
as to solve the political problems in the country.
</P>
<P>
The president denied that his reshuffle of the government last
Tuesday, in which former vice-president Brigadier General
Godfreym Iyanda, defense and foreign ministers as well as heads
of the armed forces were demoted, has relations with the October
coup.
</P>
<P>
On his talks with the Zimbabwean president, Chiluba simply
said that their meeting touched on economic, social, political as
well as defense matters.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba left this morning for Harare at the invitation by
Mugabe, and he is scheduled to return home later this afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
