<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hope of Traditional Medicine Rests with Younger Generation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Gan Chun, a young practitioner
of traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) in Nanchang, currently spends
two days a week studying under the tutelage of a senior
colleague.
</P>
<P>
"My study program will last for three years," said Gan, who has
already amassed 12 years of clinical experience in Nanchang,
capital of east China's Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 young doctors from throughout the nation, including
Gan, have been selected to study under renowned TCM experts. The
younger generation of doctors will form a "new force" to overcome
future challenges TCM will face from modern Western medicine.
</P>
<P>
"Future practitioners of TCM should not only
focus on inheriting, but also on creating," according to Cheng
Zhaosheng, an official in the Provincial Health Department.
</P>
<P>
"My current job is to summarize the academic prowess and
clinical experience of my teacher, and to transcribe them to books
in order to disseminate information," said Gan.
</P>
<P>
Gong Qiongmo, his teacher, noted that young people can approach
the development of TCM from new angles and in
turn combine it with the Western medicine. So doing will certainly
"bring a new hope to traditional Chinese medicine," said Gong.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 20 senior TCM experts in the
province, one of the country's TCM research centers, have had
successors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
