<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Take Steps to Tackle Ageing Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will take steps to
counter the negative effects on the economy brought by
the problem of ageing population, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a report delivered at an intergovernmental conference on
ageing population in the Mediterranean which ended Saturday in
Malta, Cypriot Minister of Labor and Social Insurance Efstathios
Papadakis said the number of elderly people and their ratio of
the total population in Cyprus will rise sharply in the years to
come.
</P>
<P>
By 2008, people under 15 will constitute only 20 percent of
the island's population compared with the current 24.6 percent,
while those aged over 65 will jump from a population share of 11
percent to 17.6 percent. The number of people over 75 is expected
to double to account for nearly 8 percent of the total
population, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"It is evident that ageing population is expected to have
far-reaching consequences in the labor market and the economy
of Cyprus in general, and measures should be taken urgently to
mitigate the adverse effects," Papadakis stressed.
</P>
<P>
He cited low motivation and productivity and slow adaptation
to technological change as negative indicators of an ageing
workforce.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the elderly can contribute significantly to
economic development if the right incentives and facilities such
as re-training programs were provided for them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
