<HEADLINE> Yu Genwei Scores Hat Trick as Tianjin Beats Yanbian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese national Yu Genwei
saved Tianjin Samsung temperarily from the brink of relegation
with a hat trick when the host edged Yanbian Aodong 3-2 in the
19th round of the Chinese Professional League here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Samsung, who stood 10th in the 12-team by accumulating 17
points after 18 rounds, has been suffered a long period of slump
and struggled to avoid a relegation this season.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Aodong, who has secured its status in Division A,
sent almost all its new bloods to the field since it has no chance
to battle for the top honors.
</P>
<P>
Samsung's Gao Fei curved a long pass in the midfield to the
box, where Yu picked the ball, shook off Yanbian's keeper and slot
it into the net in the 32nd minute.
</P>
<P>
Yu, who just returned from China's heart-breaking defeat in the
World Cup qualifying campaign, has been plagued with an injury and
stayed for more time on the bench than in the pitch.
</P>
<P>
The national midfielder then added two goals in the last 12
minutes of the first half.
</P>
<P>
Aodong stepped up offensive in the second half, with Huang
Dongchun narrowing the margin by scoring twice within three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
Jumping to the ninth place in the standings by collecting 20
points after the pecious win, Tianjin remained in danger of
relegation with three rounds to go.
</P>
<P>
"We are still in a difficult situation since several starters,
including Yu, Gao Yuyong and veteran Huo Jianting, are suffering
serious injuries," head coach Chen Jingang said.
</P>
<P>
Chen said Tianjin will have to win five more points in the
final three matches, including two in the road, to avoid a
disastrous relegation.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other matches, Beijing Guo'an was held to a
goaless draw by Guangzhou Apollo in a cold-hit clash, sending the
enthusiastic home crowd of 5,000 into great anger since this was
Guo'an's third consecutive home draw.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Hongyuan squandered many golden chances and had to be
satisfied with a 2-2 tie with the visiting Chinese Army.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao Hainiu suffered its fifth loss in a row as it dropped
to Shanghai Shenhua 1-3 after wasting a one-goal lead.
</P>
<P>
Dalian Wanda, who has anchored its third league champion during
four years last Thursday, was deadlocked at 0-0 by host Jinan
Taishan.
</P>
<P>
Vanguards Huangdao took a winning trip to Chengdu by beating
Sichuan Quanxing 3-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
