<HEADLINE> Serbians Vote to Choose New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Serbia's voters began to cast
their ballots Sunday to elect a new president of the republic to
replace Slebodan Milosevic, who moved to the Yugoslav presidency
in July.
</P>
<P>
The three main candidates are Foreign Minister Milan
Milutinovic who represents President Milosevic's ruling Socialist
Party (SPS), Radical Party (SRS) leader Vejislev Seselj and Vuk
Draskovic of the Serbian Renewal Movement.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's poll was held following October's presidential
election which failed when the turnout of the 7.2 million eligible
voters did not exceed the legal minimum of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
In an October run-off, Seselj, a hardline nationalist, won the
biggest share of the vote against Socialist candidate Zoren Lilic.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll in November by Ipress said 36 percent of the
electorate would be given to Milutinovic, 34 percent for Seselj
and 15 percent for Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
Observers said Sunday's election might also be invalidated due
to voter apathy and a low-key campaign and an opposition boycott.
</P>
<P>
If none of the three candidates gets an overall majority in
Sunday's re-run, a run-off between the top two candidates will be
held, probably on December 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
