<HEADLINE> Afghan Shiite Faction Releases Taliban prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 7 (Xinhua) -- An Afghan Shiite faction
opposing Islamic Taliban militia today unilaterally released 10
Taliban captives held in their stronghold in central Afghanistan,
a Red Cross spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The released Taliban men are due to be transported from the
Hezb-e-Wahdat base Bamyan to the Taliban-held eastern Afghan city
of Jalalabad on Monday by a plane operated by the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), announced the spokesman in
Kabul, the Afghan capital, according to a report monitored here
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"We feel something good has started and that this is a positive
step," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that, the Hezb-e-Wadhat, which is allied with two other
anti-Taliban forces led by Uzbek warlord Rashid Dostum and former
Afghan military chief Ahmad Masood, unilaterally decided to
release 10 of the 80 Taliban fighters they reportedly held.
</P>
<P>
Hezb-e-Wadhat's decision came only days after Dostum and Masood
released 99 Taliban prisoners from their prison camps.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have been battling the coalition forces in central
and northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The hard-line militia have insisted that they would not enter
any negotiations with the rival alliance before the release of all
their prisoners held in the north while the alliance has set the
demilitarization of Kabul as one of their conditions for peace
talks with Taliban.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
