<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Potash Fertilizer Production Plant Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A microbial potash
fertilizer production plant, one of the largest plants of its kind
in the world, has entered operations in Baoding, north China's
Hebei Province
</P>
<P>
The Microbial Research Institute under the Chinese Academy of
Science commenced construction of the plant in 1996. Construction
of the facility, listed as one of the country's major trial
industrial projects, was completed at a cost of some 32 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The plant produces "Juwei" brand microbial potash fertilizer
which is highly popular with Chinese farmers due to its low price,
high-level effectiveness and pollution-free characteristics.
</P>
<P>
"Juwei" produced during the plant's trial operation period has
been shipped to 27 provinces and regions for application on more
than 30 crops planted on four million hectares. The product was
also exported to India, Thailand, Malaysia, and Viet Nam.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 10,000 tons of microbial potash fertilizer
applied to more than 1.3 million ha. of farmland can increase
output by between 300-400 million kg annually.
</P>
<P>
India has decided to join hands with the Microbial Research
Institute under the Hebei Academy of Sciences to construct a
similar plant with an annual microbial potash fertilizer
production capacity of 3,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
China currently has over 20 million ha. of farmland with a
critical shortage of potassium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
