<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Expected to Meet Annual Economic Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Official statistics indicate
that South China's Guangdong Province will most likely to achieve
its economic goals for this year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics provided by the Guangdong Provincial Statistics
Bureau show that the province's gross domestic product grew by
10.4 percent in the first nine months of this year compared with
the same period of last year and the inflation rate this year fell
to a record low for recent years.
</P>
<P>
Projections calls for Guangdong's annual economic growth rate
to hit 10 percent, with the inflation rate remaining below 0.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Related statistics indicate that Guangdong has entered a period
of appropriate economic growth and low inflation, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Further analysis shows that the industrial output value of the
province, a showcase of China's market-oriented economic reform,
reached 598.6 billion yuan for the first three quarters of this
year, up 18.7 percent on the previous year's figure.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's retail sales volume for the first nine months
grew 13.8 percent to 209.8 billion yuan, with foreign trade
surging 26 percent to 52.1 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's fiscal revenues and expenditures for the first
three quarters rose 21.5 percent and 16.2 percent
respectively. The per capita income of urban residents for the
period reached 6,518 yuan, with the income level of farmers
standing at 2,662 yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
