<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Poverty Alleviation, Unending Story For </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- For the Himalayan kingdom of
Nepal, poverty alleviation is an unending story, simply because it
is among the poorest not only in the South Asia region but also in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Even though there have been concerted efforts during the past
four decades to improve the economic condition, the GNP per capita
of 190 U.S. dollars for Nepal is one of the lowest in the world
and has remained stagnant for a considerable length of time, noted
the 1997 Report on Human Development in South Asia produced by the
Human Development Center in Islamabad, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
About 45 percent, or 9.45 million of the Nepalese population
still live below the poverty line. Over four-fifths of the total
population have no access to sanitation and nearly one-half
without access to safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
And worse still, an estimated 100,000 individuals are forced to
work as bonded laborers. Of the total eight million children in
Nepal, five million have to work to support their families, said a
survey conducted by the National Planning Commission (NPC).
</P>
<P>
"Poverty in Nepal is the result of multiple interwoven
factors," said Narendra B. Amatya, undersecretary in charge of the
Poverty Alleviation Section in the NPC.
</P>
<P>
"We have limited cultivable land area and we have no natural
resources," Mr.Amatya told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Only 17 percent of the land in Nepal is arable, while 68
percent is in the hilly area and 15 percent in the mountainous
area.
</P>
<P>
Though abundant in water resources, Nepal produces a meagre 237
megawatts of hydro-electric power, or less than one percent of its
potential.
</P>
<P>
Underdeveloped physical infrastructure like road and
telecommunications are also blamed for poverty, Mr.Amatya said.
</P>
<P>
"Then we have problem of human resources development. We lack
capital and technology," he said.
</P>
<P>
Frequent changes of government also affect Nepal's social and
economic development, he added.
</P>
<P>
Poverty alleviation has been one of the major objectives of
Nepali governments and a number of programs have been launched in
the past years.
</P>
<P>
Since agriculture has been contributing to over 40 percent of
the gross domestic product (GDP) and providing 82 percent of the
employment, the programs have been focusing on rural areas and
putting high priority on the development of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In the Eighth Five-Year Plan period (1992-1997), a Rural
Self-reliance Program was launched, under which the central
government allocated a fund of 500,000 rupees (about 10,000 U.S.
dollars) to each of the 4,000 village development committees (VDC)
in the country's 75 districts, and allowed the VDCs to deduct 75
percent of the land tax at their disposal for local development.
</P>
<P>
The VDCs were authorized to decide for their own development
projects, but must have the women directly involved in at least
one project. The central government would provide technical
assistance wherever necessary.
</P>
<P>
This program has turned out a success in accelerating the
building of infrastructure and social services institutions like
road, schools, clinics, irrigation facilities and drinking water
projects.
</P>
<P>
Other successful programs include the Small Farmers Development
Program and the Production Credit for Rural Women. The first
program had such promising components as group liability and
savings and intensive technical support, while the second
organized groups of village women for developmental activities and
small-scale business undertakings for which they received
subsidized commercial financing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Processing Sector Gains Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The processing sector
accounted for the largest share of China's foreign trade in the
first nine months of this year, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
China's processing trade grew by 16.8 percent to 120.8 billion
US dollars for the first three quarters of this year and accounted
for 53 percent of total imports and exports during the period,
according to an official from the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The official told participants of a recent symposium
that processing trade expanded by an average 22 percent
between 1988 and 1996, rising from 29.3 billion US dollars to
146.6 billion US dollars during the period. In addition, the
proportion of processing trade to total trade grew from 28.5
percent to 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, foreign-funded enterprises have replaced
state-owned collective enterprises as the main contributors to the
rapidly growing processing trade sector. Foreign-funded
enterprises accounted for 64 percent of China's total processing
trade in 1996, up 14 percent on 1988.
</P>
<P>
Rapid growth in the processing trade has been recorded in both
highly developed coastal areas and less developed interior
provinces and regions, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
He noted that processing trade in capital- and
technology-intensive products has reached a considerably higher
level in recent years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Poverty Alleviation, Unending Story For </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Nepali parliament passed the Amendment Bill on
Land Reforms in October 1996, which guarantees the ownership right
of the 370,000 registered tenants over the land they till. Earlier
a tiller could not claim such a right.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government has also been seeking international
cooperation in its efforts to alleviate poverty. Nepal's Makwanpur
district participated in the "SAARC Seven Sisters: District
Development Coordination and Improved Poverty Project Design"
launched in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
Five other member countries of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) -- Bangladesh, India, the Maldives,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka -- also joined the project. Bhutan did not.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, six district-level fora were established.
They periodically reviewed and monitored the ongoing poverty
alleviation programs in the districts and identified the best
practices for replication and diagnosed possible problems and
constraints to redress them.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Nepal has been putting high priority on poverty
alleviation in its cooperation with donors, which include the
World Bank, the Asian Development Bank and a dozen of developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have borne fruit. "At the beginning of the Eighth
Five-Year Plan period, the level of poverty was 49 percent. Now it
has come down to 45 percent," Mr.Amatya said.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth Five-Year Plan (1997-2002) implemented as of July 15,
has set poverty alleviation as its major objective and envisages
lowering the poverty line first to 32.56 percent under the ninth
plan, then to 22.5 percent and 15 percent respectively under the
10th (2002-2007) and 11th plans (2007-2012), and finally to 10
percent under the 12th plan (2012-2017).
</P>
<P>
The focus is on production, food security, employment, increase
in income, supply of fertilizers, irrigation facilities, rural
roads, electrification and technology suitable to the agriculture
ecology.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, new special programs will be introduced for the
various communities especially in the remote areas, special
national tribes and socially oppressed communities.
</P>
<P>
A Poverty Alleviation Fund of 40 million rupees (about 650,000
U.S. dollars) will be set up to develop and expand the agro-based
industries.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Perspective Plan (APP) has also been introduced
this year with the objective of attaining high growth rate and
contributing to poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
In the first year of the ninth plan period, the APP will run an
integrated program by coordinating irrigation, technology
development and publicity, loan, production materials, rural roads
and electrification.
</P>
<P>
"Provided that we have good planning, good social mobilization
and we put in hard work, there is no reason why we should not be
able to achieve our goals," Mr.Amatya said.
</P>
<P>
But he acknowledged that his country is facing some quite
serious problems which are proving "big stumbling blocks in the
way of our national development and poverty alleviation."
</P>
<P>
The first is Nepal has only 17 percent land area under
cultivation and the second is there are no any significant
off-farm activity, he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that 82 percent of the population are engaging in
agriculture, but the agricultural activities last for only six to
seven months. "For the rest of the time, they have no
income-generating activities, so unemployment is as high as 40
percent in the rural areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
The third serious problem is the overgrowth of population,
which is growing at a rate of 2.6 percent annually. "Because the
population pressure, whatever we achieve it eluded," Mr.Amatya
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
