<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Universities Experimenting With Non-Major Degree Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Jingyi, one of the first
group of students to graduate from China's Nanchang University in
Jiangxi Province who will be out looking for a job next year, does
not seem too worried about his prospects.
</P>
<P>
"I've taken almost all the science and engineering courses at
the university and think I have a wider range of possibilities in
looking for jobs," he says.
</P>
<P>
The university stopped offering majors for students
like Zhu three years ago, as an experiment in education reforms
and has enrolled more than 200 students, according to Wang
Maoxiang, a dean at the university.
</P>
<P>
Wang says that they plan to extend the experiment to liberal
arts courses.
</P>
<P>
Nanchang University was formed in 1993 by merging Jiangxi
University with Jiangxi Industrial University. More and more
students from the university were facing difficulties in finding a
job. So it tried to give them a wider field to choose from and
a more solid foundation, Wang explains.
</P>
<P>
Some other colleges and universities, including prestigious
Fudan University, have decided to experiment in similar fashion.
</P>
<P>
Yang Fujia, president of Fudan University, says that
departments there will not be divided into specific majors, but
will try to build students' adaptability to the society.
</P>
<P>
According to a source in the State Education Commission, the
current 500 majors in China's colleges and universities will be
reduced by half by June, next year.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Shaosen, deputy-director of the Jiangxi Provincial
Education Commission, says that the current majors in Chinese
colleges and universities are set by the State and are too
specific to meet the needs for the growth of the market-oriented
economy in China.
</P>
<P>
"More versatile and talented people are needed by the society,"
he says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
