<HEADLINE> LIMA Exhibition Concludes Successfully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The six-day Langkawi
International Maritime and Aerospace (LIMA `97) Exhibition
concluded today as a success.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir said LIMA `97 was successful
despite the country's economic problems because it has "got
nothing to do with the economic situation."
</P>
<P>
"Companies participating in LIMA `97 are not suffering from the
economic situation, except some Malaysian companies," he told a
news conference at the end of the exhibition, the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama reported from langkawi, some 500
kilometers north from here.
</P>
<P>
About 60 per cent of 950 exhibitors from the aerospace and
maritime industries present this year have verbally confirmed
their participation for next LIMA Exhibition in 1999, which
Mahathir said would be bigger and more attractive compared to LIMA
'97.
</P>
<P>
This year for the first time, the maritime show was held
separately from the aerospace show to serve the industries better.
</P>
<P>
LIMA '97 was the fourth in the series with the first LIMA
Exhibition held in 1991, the second in 1993, and the third in
1995.
</P>
<P>
LIMA Exhibition has been ranked the world's fourth largest
airshow after Farnborough, Paris and Dubai.
</P>
<P>
A total of 21,000 trade visitors attended this year's LIMA
Exhibition, according to the report quoting official sources.
</P>
