<HEADLINE> Wild Gingko Trees Discovered in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A group of wild gingko trees
on Jinfo Mountain near Chongqing Municipality, in the southwestern
part of the country, are thought to be a possible source of gingko
trees.
</P>
<P>
The group of trees was discovered in the primeval forest on
Jinfo on November 27 by a group of Chinese botanists and forestry
workers. More than 500 of the trees are over 50 years old, and a
dozen are more than 1,000 years old. The tallest, at 26 meters in
height and 11.6 meters in girth, is over 2,500 years old.
</P>
<P>
According to county records, the earliest residents in the area
came during the later Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), only about 100
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Gingko trees go back to the age of dinosaurs, over two million
years ago. Many foreign countries have imported gingko trees from
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
