<HEADLINE> World Court Fixes Dates to Sit for Bakassi Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Court of
Justice at the Hague has fixed March 2 to 11 next year for
hearing in the case concerning the border dispute between Nigeria
and Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
Today's Sunday Tribune newspaper quoted a court statement as
saying that the sitting will be dedicated exclusively to oral
arguments of the parties concerning Nigeria's preliminary
objections to Cameroon's case.
</P>
<P>
Both Nigeria and Cameroon have claimed territorial sovereignty
over the oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula and repeated clashes have
been reported since 1994, when Cameroon instituted proceedings
against Nigeria in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
While also accusing Nigeria of militarily occupying the
peninsula, Cameroon asked the court to declare the occupation
unlawful and to cause Nigeria to withdraw unconditionally and pay
reparation for the damage.
</P>
<P>
About two months after the first application in March 1994,
Cameroon again filed an additional application to extend the case
to cover what it alleged is its territory in Lake Chad Area now
occupied by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria subsequently contended that the court has no
jurisdiction in the case and that Cameroon's grievances are
inadmissible, according to the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency said the court has explained that by
provisions of its statute, it has to decided on preliminary
objections before proceeding to the merits of the case.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's former Minister of Justice, Chief Michael Agbamuche,
went to the court as attorney-general of the federation to meet
the president at the Hague more than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
On his return, the former minister said the court had fixed
March for the hearing and judgement would be delivered in June
next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
