<HEADLINE> Low Turn-out Marks Nigeria's State Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's state assembly
election Saturday was marked by low turn-out amid a generally
peaceful atmosphere, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos city, a polling station with 350 registered voters
recorded only 30 ballots. Another with 485 registered voters also
collected some 30 votes.
</P>
<P>
Investigation by Xinhua show the same story. A polling station
on the Victoria Island saw less than 20 of its 790 registered
voters turning out to vote.
</P>
<P>
The low turn-out, in fact, has been forecast by media surveys
before the election. Except a few people who said they feel a
responsibility towards the success of democracy, most of the
interviewed people said they would not go to vote.
</P>
<P>
The most cited reasons for not going to vote are general
indifference to politics, little knowledge of the candidates and
disappointment of government policies.
</P>
<P>
Despite the low turn-out, the election was undergone in a
generally orderly and peaceful atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
This was made possible by the large presence of police and
security agents and traffic restrictions. The low turn-out itself
also helped.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, there were some slight hitches and
confusions during the election, but none of them was serious
enough to affect the fairness of the whole election.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election will produce about 990 state legislative
seats, contested by the country's five political parties.
</P>
<P>
The election is part of the military government's transition
to civil rule program. It will be followed by a national congress
election in April next year and a presidential election in
August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
