<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians To Vote Delegates For Constitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Australians have just two days
left to mail their votes for delegates to the next year's
constitutional convention which will debate whether or not
Australia should become a republic.
</P>
<P>
Special Minister of State Nick Minchin in a statement issued
today urged all voters to exercise their right to shape the
convention due to begin February next year.
</P>
<P>
"The convention will be an occasion of great national
significance, with potentially a very big influence on the way
Australia is governed in the future," Minchin said.
</P>
<P>
All ballot papers must be received by the Australian Electoral
Commission (AEC) by 6pm on December 9. Papers can be hand
delivered and the AEC will continue reissuing voting papers to
replace lost packages until just before the close of polls on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ballot will elect 76 delegates to join the 76 delegates
already appointed by the government to the convention.
</P>
<P>
Newly-appointed Australian Democrats Deputy Leader Natasha
Stott Despoja today criticized the constitutional convention
process as failing to represent young people in Australia.
</P>
<P>
She said she was concerned that 34 percent of young people had
not received ballot papers for the convention, "I've been
concerned all along that the constitutional convention don't
necessarily reflect the diversity and difference that's evident in
our population," Despoja told Network Ten's 'Meet the Press'
program.
</P>
<P>
"And that of course means young people are usually not
represented," it was particularly distressing as 30 percent of
Australia's population were under 30 years of age, she said.
</P>
<P>
The convention, to decide if the Constitution should be changed
to create a republic and which model to adopt and a timetable for
change, will take place over 10 days next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
