<HEADLINE> Mubarak Meets with Arafat on US Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today held talks with visiting Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat on the U.S. efforts to salvage the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived here Saturday night from Geneva, briefed
Mubarak on the outcome of his talks with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright in the Swiss city.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's Political Advisor Osama el-Baz later joined the
meeting together with Secretary-General of the PLO Executive
Committee Mahmoud Abbas, PNA Minister of Planning and
International Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath and member of Fatah
Central Committee Hani al Hassan.
</P>
<P>
In Geneva, Albright, stepping up efforts to break the Mideast
peace deadlock, said after talks with Arafat that she would meet
him and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu separately later
this month somewhere in western Europe for the second time in a
month.
</P>
<P>
Albright met with Netanyahu in Paris on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Senior U.S. officials said that Albright had asked the two
leaders to make decisions on key peace issues before the meetings.
</P>
<P>
In hopes of staging "final status" Israeli-Palestinian talks,
Albright is pushing Israel to carry out a new troop withdrawal in
the West Bank and freeze Jewish settlements, and the Palestinians
to crack down on extremists.
</P>
<P>
But Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zahdi Kedra, in statements
to the Middle East News Agency Saturday, said the PNA is
determined not to engage in the final status negotiations until
Israel implemented commitments stipulated in the signed accords.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is to leave here later today for Doha, en route to
Tehran to attend the 8th Organization of the Islamic Conference
(OIC) slated for Tuesday in Iran.
</P>
<P>
This will be Arafat's first visit to Tehran in more than a
decade. The Palestinians hope the Islamic summit would take a
strong stand on Jerusalem issue to protect Muslim shrines in the
holy city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
