<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tiny Village Takes Election of Deputy Seriously </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- An election for deputy to the
Fifth People's Congress of Lhunze County, Tibet, is going on at
Yumai village, perhaps the world's smallest administrative region
in terms of population, with only 18 villagers.
</P>
<P>
Zhouga, head of the village on the southern slope of the
Himalayas, said that "despite our small population, villagers
attach great importance to the election as it embodies our
democratic rights."
</P>
<P>
For thousands of years the village, which covers an area of
1,900 square kilometers and lies 600 kilometers southwest of
Lhasa, capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region, remains separated
from the rest of the world by snow-capped mountains during winter.
</P>
<P>
However, remarkable changes have taken place in recent
years. With the help of local government villagers now have access
to a hospital, schools and TV, which they had never heard of years
before.
</P>
<P>
"We used to live a lonely life during the six-month period when
we were cut off from the rest of the world by heavy snow," said
Sanggyai Paqu, father of Zhouga, whose family of three had been
the only one in the village until last year.
</P>
<P>
The boundless land of the village is a natural pastureland, but
not suitable for agriculture, as a result "all grain and
vegetables we eat had to be bought from outside of the village
before winter," said Sanggyai, "and the bumpy journey usually
takes seven to eight hours even for good horse riders."
</P>
<P>
Each year, Sanggyai's family would weave all sorts of bamboo
articles and sell them at fairs held outside the village. In
return, they would bring back clothes, salt and other daily
necessities.
</P>
<P>
Personnel from the autonomous region's department of
communications have surveyed the topography of the village. "It
seems that a highway, which is bound to tie the village closer
with the rest of the world, is expected to be built in the
foreseeable future," Zhouga said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese City Maintaining Growth in Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The city of Shantou in south
China's Guangdong Province had 3.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
exports in the first ten months of this year, up 65.5 percent from
the same period last year, continuing its growth in exports, local
officials say.
</P>
<P>
There are 57 overseas-funded enterprises in the city, each with
exports worth 10 million U.S. dollars, according to statistics,
which is the result of combined efforts of the foreign trade
department and the local commodity inspection bureau.
</P>
<P>
During the first ten months, an audit revealed 124 money-losing
enterprises, which have now been closed down or had their
operations changed.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the commodity inspection bureau has been providing
ISO9000 evaluation services for large and medium-sized enterprises
and overseas-funded companies to help them ensure the quality of
export products.
</P>
<P>
The city has also been expanding its overseas market. Some 32
trade organizations have visited 26 countries and regions this
year bringing back 14 million U.S. dollars worth of contracts on
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
