<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf to Build Integrated Power Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The six members of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) today decided to build their power
systems into an integrated network, the Kuwaiti News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The electricity ministers of the countries made the decision in
Riyadh, capital of Saudi Arabia, after examining the results of a
meeting of the project's founding committee, according to the
agency.
</P>
<P>
The project is intended for the six countries to share their
power surplus, saving them from building more power stations, said
Qatari Minister of Power and Water Ahmed Mohammed Ali al-Sebaie,
who chaired the meeting of the ministers.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain and Qatar are asked to contribute
35 percent of the 2.2-billion-U.S.-dollar cost in the first phase
of the project, and the remainder will be secured through bank
loans, al-Sebaie said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that once the second phase begins, the shares of
the cost by the United Arab Emirates and Oman will be specified.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari minister anticipated that the project would start in
three or four years.
</P>
<P>
GCC, a political, economic and defense alliance set up in 1981,
groups Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Oman, Bahrain and Qatar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Seeks Islamic Help in Lifting UN Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad
Saeed Al-Sahhaf said here today that his country will seek Islamic
countries' help in lifting the U.N. sanctions imposed on it.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf made the remarks to reporters on the sidelines of the
on-going foreign ministerial meeting of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC), preceding the OIC summit scheduled for
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf said the issue of the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions
on his country will be raised at the OIC foreign ministerial
meeting.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed that Baghdad has stopped selling its oil in
protest against the United Nations' disagreement with Iraq's
demands for needed goods.
</P>
<P>
"As long as the U.N. does not agree with Iraqi demands for
purchase and distribution of basic commodities needed by the
country (Iraq), we will not export our oil," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government announced Friday that the country will
not sell oil under a U.N.-extended third term until its
grievances over delays in food and medical supplies are met.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here also said that the Iraqi crude oil sales
through Turkey stopped early Friday right after the end of the
second term of the oil-for-food deal between the U.N. and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government has repeatedly complained that the
implementation of the oil-for-food programs was delayed under the
pressure of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to export 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to buy badly needed
food, medicine and other humanitarian goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
