<HEADLINE> Turkish PM to Seek Support for EU Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz is to pay visits to Britain and Luxembourg on December 9 and
10 to rally support for Turkey's European Union (EU) membership
bid.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz will explain to his British counterpart Tony Blair
Turkey's expectations for full EU membership during his one-day
visit in London, said a Foreign Ministry statement issued here
today.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey will ask Britain's help on the issue of Turkey's
inclusion in the planned EU enlargement process," it said.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz will fly to Luxembourg December 10 to meet his
Luxembourg counterpart Jean-Claude Juncker on Ankara's EU bid.
</P>
<P>
He will persuade Juncker, whose country holds the current EU
term presidency, to take a positive stance concerning this issue,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The EU summit is reportedly scheduled to be held in Luxembourg
later this month to finalize the policy of expanding the European
body.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been sparing no effort to strive for a full EU
membership since 1987, but so far little substantial progress has
been made due to its differences with EU, especially Germany, over
a number of issues.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, Juncker held talks with Yilmaz and Turkish
Foreign Minister Ismail Cem in Istanbul, Turkey's largest city,
but failing to give Turks an encouraging message. 
</P>
