<HEADLINE> Ousted Afghan President Requests for Seat at OIC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The ousted President of
Afghanistan Burhanuddin Rabbani has requested the seat of his
country at the forthcoming Islamic summit be granted to his
government, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
To grant the seat to the government of Afghanistan recognized
by the United Nations will help preserve the territorial integrity
of the country, Rabbani said in an interview with the news agency.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan's seat at the summit of the Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC) due 9-11 this month was announced to remain
vacant at a meeting of the foreign ministers of the OIC members
earlier this year due to the serious conflicts in the war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani slammed the recent offensives in northeastern
Afghanistan and the absence from a peace conference by the
Taleban, the Islamic militant group which drove him out of the
capital Kabul in September last year.
</P>
<P>
"Taleban's military operations and its absence from the Isfahan
peace conference is indicative of its warmongering policies," said
Rabbani, claiming that the anti-Taleban United Islamic Front is
dependable to bring peace and tranquility in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A peace conference was held last week in Iran's central city of
Isfahan by leaders of Afghan factions, including Rabbani, former
prime minister Gulbuddin Hekmatyar and former northern Afghan
opposition warlord Abdul Malik. But it was boycotted by the Taleban.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iran's special representative for Afghanistan
Alaeddin Boroujerdi said today that the OIC summit will discuss
the possibility to hold an Afghanistan peace conference in
parallel to the summit.
</P>
<P>
If possible, the conference will be held in Iranian capital
Tehran with the participation of five of the neighbors of
Afghanistan as well as Saudi Arabia, Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
</TEXT>
