<HEADLINE> Iraq Complains Heavy Losses by UN Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHARJAH, UAE, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Minister of Trade
Mohammed Mehdi Saleh said here today that his country has
sustained disastrous losses of lives and revenues brought about by
the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters during an Arab-African fair which opened
here today that Iraq has lost 120 billion U.S. dollars after Iraq
was banned from exporting oil, its major revenue earner.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that 125 million Iraqi women and children have
died of the lack of food and medicines since the sanctions were
imposed after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister described the sanctions as "the most severe
and comprehensive" ever in the human history.
</P>
<P>
However, Saleh said that despite the "disasters," Iraq has
managed to be "self-sufficient in vegetables and fruits."
</P>
<P>
Iraq also has successfully utilized its iron resources in the
country's reconstruction process following the 1991 Gulf War, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the oil-for-food agreement between the U.N. and
Iraq, Saleh complained that since the deal came to effect a year
ago, Iraq has only got 35 million U.S. dollars of the total
incomes of 2.35 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the oil-exporting earnings "has gone to the United
Nations, special commissions and some persons in the commissions,"
he claimed.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official called for the investigation of the funds
which are put in the French Bank to "show the world where the
money went." The funds should be used to buy food for Iraqi
children and save their lives instead, he added.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to sell 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil for every six months to buy humanitarian
supplies.
</P>
<P>
Saleh stressed the importance of boosting his country's
cooperation with all Arab countries in the field of importing food.
</P>
<P>
Saleh arrived here today for the third African-Arab fair. But
there is no Iraqi delegation due to "transporting and other
special conditions," Saleh said.
</P>
<P>
The seven-day fair was staged under the auspices of the Arab
League and the Organization of African Unity. A total of 60
countries took part in the fair and a number of U.N. organizations
also attended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
