<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Trade Union Resumes Nationwide Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Trade Union resumed
nationwide strike this morning as it failed to reach an agreement
with the Finance Ministry over pension reform, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Trade Union leader Amir Perez said today that he had informed
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and President Ezer
Weizman that the negotiations between striking workers and the
Treasury have fallen through.
</P>
<P>
Some 700,000 workers took part in the strike which was
launched Wednesday in protest against government plans for wages
reform and privatization. And today's strike will spread to
workers of the education system and public transportation.
</P>
<P>
The Trade Union permitted the striking workers to return to
work over the weekend in a bid to pave the way to renew
negotiations with the Treasury Saturday night. And it had
threatened to intensify the strike if the talks failed.
</P>
<P>
One of the key sticking points during the negotiations
was to reach compromise over the pension agreement signed in May
1996 by Perez and former finance minister Avraham Shohat, which,
current Minister of Finance Ya'acov Neeman, with Netanyahu's full
backing, refuses to uphold.
</P>
<P>
The Trade Union is demanding the agreement be retroactively
enforced, while the Treasury says it is prepared to allow
implementation from January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Paris Saturday night during his European trip,
Netanyahu said that he has been in constant touch with Neeman and
he hoped that the workers will end their strike.
</P>
<P>
The damage to the economy from the first three day of the
strike, which has paralyzed the country by effectively shutting
down airports, seaports, banks, government offices and
state-owned industries, was estimated at some 150 million to 200
million shekels (about 42 million to 57 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Labor Court will hold a hearing on the
State Attorney's demand to impose fine on Trade Union leaders and
heads of workers' committees for continuing the strike despite the
back-to-work orders issued last week.
</P>
<P>
The strike is the latest round in the Trade Union's battle
against government economic reform plans, which have sparked
fears that worker's rights would be harmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
