<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippine Economy Slows Down in Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Impacted by the financial crisis
sweeping much of Asia, the Philippine economy slowed down in the
first three quarters of this year, growing by six percent compared
with 7.3 percent in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts forecast that the economic growth would be even slower
next year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the country's economy had been growing steadily
thanks to the Fidel Ramos administration's reform efforts to
revive the economy and measures to stabilize the political
situation. The gross national product (GNP) grew by an annual
average of more than one percent from 1.4 percent in 1992 to 6.8
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
With its economic achievements and the successful holding of
the 4th informal leadership meeting of the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum last year, the Philippines was dubbed by
some international organizations "a new economic tiger" in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
However, the tiger fell sick this year. Its economy showed
sluggish signs in the first six months, registering a mere 5.9
percent growth compared with the year-ago level of 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Then it was hit by the region-wide financial turmoil which
started in Thailand in July and has spread to South Korea and
Japan. The Philippine peso has since devaluated by at least 35
percent to about 35 pesos against the U.S. dollar now. The
composite index of the local stock market has also fallen by a
third.
</P>
<P>
To defend the peso, the Central Bank has depleted the country's
gross international reserve to 10.3 billion dollars from 12
billion dollars early this year.
</P>
<P>
The adverse effects of the crisis have been felt in most
sectors of the Philippine economy. Industrial growth in the third
quarter dropped by one percent to 5.8 percent compared with the
second quarter, manufacturing shrank to 4.5 percent and the
service sector, a pillar of the economy, fell by one percent to
5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government's budget went into the red for first
time in four years, posting a 2.3 billion peso (65 million
dollars) deficit so far this year. Due to higher interest rates,
the business sector also reported a fall of at least 10 percent in
business since the beginning of the currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, the country was also struck by the El Nino weather
phenomenon. Suffering from a drought caused by El Nino, the
country's agriculture, which grew by 4 percent last year, has
slowed down to only 1.1 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, insisted that the country was the
least affected in the financial turmoil and its economic
fundamentals remained strong. It said the country's banks remained
healthy and major economic indicators were sound when compared
with neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 months of this year, the country's exports grew
by 23 percent, slashing the trade deficit to 830 million dollars
from 11.3 billion dollars recorded a year earlier. Total
investments reached 15.3 billion dollars in the 10-month period,
up by 366 percent compared with the year-ago level, and inflation
stood at a low level of 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"In view of these, we are quite confident that we can actually
end the year within the 5.5 to 6 percent revised projection that
we have for GNP", said Economic Development Secretary Cielito
Habito. The Philippines would be "the first tiger out of the wood"
(the financial storm) next year with a GNP growth of 5 to 5.3
percent and a gross domestic product (GDP) growth of 6 to 7
percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
But the International Monetary Fund (IMF), from which the
Philippines is scheduled to exit before the year-end, has a
different viewpoint. It forecast that the country could manage an
economic growth of only 4 to 4.5 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IMF arrived at this conclusion after sending a team to
examine the Philippines' economic conditions last month. It held
that the country's current account deficit and foreign debt were
too big, having reached 3.5 billion dollars and 44 billion
dollars, or 4.2 percent and 50 percent of the GDP respectively.
</P>
<P>
Things are likely to get worse before they could get better for
the economy, analysts said. They said the adverse effects of the
financial crisis would be in full blow next year and the economic
growth would be even slower until the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, adjustments would have to be made in the 1998
economic growth targets," Habito said, adding that the high
interest rates and El Nino would dampen growth.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the financial meltdown, other threats to the economy
also exist -- Some 35 percent of the Filipinos are living in
poverty, economic growth is felt only by the rich and in the
capital region, infrastructure is seriously inadequate and
kidnappings, corruption and other crimes are widespread in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Political instability is also threatening economic growth. Some
business leaders have accused President Ramos and his supporters
of paying attention only to revising the Constitution in order to
extend the term of Ramos and of neglecting the economic slowdown
and the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Next year, the presidential election will take the center stage
in the Philippines. Whether a new president would be elected
smoothly? Will he or she continue Ramos' reforms? Or will the new
president be able to find new ways to boost the economy?
Economists believed that all these factors would affect next
year's economic growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
