<HEADLINE> Flood Displaces 70,000 People in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Flood in north-western Uganda
has displaced 70,000 people, "The Monitor" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Uganda Red Cross (URC) said the 70,000 homeless resident of
Jonam County, Nebbi District now are camped in Ojigo Catholic
Mission.
</P>
<P>
Peter Oryem, the secretary of URC, said the flood was caused
by torrential rains last week.
</P>
<P>
The Nile flood in the district was reinforced by the high
water in its tributes of Ora from Zaire and Ome from the Kitgum
District, east of the disaster area.
</P>
<P>
In eastern Mbale District, URC started its distribution of
relief supplies to the resident in the flood-affected areas from
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Omollo, the acting chief delegate of International Red
Cross and Red Crescent Society said a report on the assessment of the
disaster situation in Mbale and Tororo districts
has sent to their headquarters in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the two districts were reportedly out of
control.
</P>
<P>
In the west, a day long thunder storm left Bundibugyo District
virtually cut off from the rest of the country. Road from Fort
Portal to Bundibugyo impassable since two bridges on the road
were swept away. Passengers commuting between the two towns were
stranded on the way. This is the third time the road between the
two towns were cut off this rain season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
