<HEADLINE> March Calling for Peace Launched in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Some ten thousand people
took part in a march Sunday morning through Cambodia's capital of
Phnom Penh calling for peace.
</P>
<P>
Banners inscribed with slogans such as "Strive for peace" and
"Realize national reconciliation" were held by the participants
during the march, which was organized by the Khmer Nations Party
(KNP).
</P>
<P>
The people, headed by KNP President Sam Rainsy, marched for
more than two hours before they arrived at a temple in the suburbs
of the city, where they held a ceremony to pray for peace in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
A 38-year-old disabled veteran told Xinhua that the war in
Cambodia which lasted several decades has effected serious
disasters, causing innumerable people dead or disabled.
</P>
<P>
"Although no large-scale battles have broken out since 1993,
there is still no real national reconciliation. I lost my leg
during a battle near the border with Thailand last year," he added.
</P>
<P>
"My purpose of marching is to express the hope that the real
national reconciliation and peace would be realized and no
tragedies would occur any more in Cambodia," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
