<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Companies Become Victims of Web Racket </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Some "pirate" operators
have been deliberately registering the names of South African
companies on the Internet and then demanding money from them if
they want to use their own names on a Web site, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Since this is reaching alarming proportions, companies are
urged to register their domain names even if they are not
considering a Web address in the foreseeable future, according to
the Sunday Tribune newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"The disturbing fact is that because the amounts the pirates
charge companies to hand over their domain names are not that
high, usually no more than 5,000 or 6,000 Rand (1,040 or 1,250
U.S. Dollars), so most companies simply pay up rather than take
the more costly litigation route," said Douglas Reed, a computer
company executive.
</P>
<P>
But the ransom money could be very high, Reed warned.
</P>
<P>
A domain name registration costs only 200 Rand (a little more
than 40 Dollars). Therefore, even companies not planning a Web
site could find registration good insurance for their brands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
