<HEADLINE> Cost Of Keeping Pets In Shanghai Goes Up Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- China's leading economic and
financial center has increased the cost of keeping a pet dog --
from 200 yuan (about 24 US dollars) to 2,000 yuan a year.
</P>
<P>
A new regulation from the Municipal Finance Bureau, which is
intended to slow the increase in the number of dogs, says that dog
owners in urban districts will have to pay the municipal
government that amount each year, while dog owners in the
outskirts will pay 1,000 yuan, farmers, 100 yuan, a year. The
former is a five-fold increase and the latter is twice the old
amount.
</P>
<P>
The city began to collect pet dog fees in 1994. The number of
dogs in urban districts has fallen from 8,000 in 1994 to 5,000
today, while the number in rural areas has fallen from 70,000 to
10,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
