<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Takes Measures to Save Wildlife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Contingency measures have been put
in place around Zimbabwe's national parks to cushion the effects of
the impending drought on wild animals, the Sunday Mail reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Both the government and wildlife non-governmental organisations
are keeping a keen eye on the El Nino situation to ensure that there
is a recurrence of the 1992 drought which saw almost half of the
wildlife population being killed in the country.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a spokesperson for the Ministry of Mines,
Environment and Tourism, saying that mechanisms have been put in place
in every national park to ensure the safety of animals if the country
does not get normal rains this season which started in November.
</P>
<P>
The spokesperson said the ministry paid particular attention to
water situations.
</P>
<P>
The country's largest wildlife group, Wildlife Society, has a
program to ensure that water is available for animals. The group
is taking seriously warnings from meteorologists that Zimbabwe and the
region are likely to have one of their worst droughts because of the
El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
''Right now we are still monitoring the water situation in all
parks. However, we won't be caught unaware like what happened in
1992, because we managed to drill boreholes in every park in addition
to natural water points,'' said Chief Executive of the Widlife
Society Ian Cormack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
