<HEADLINE> Zambian President Warns Against Tribalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has warned aspiring candidates in the ongoing Copperbelt
provincial elections of the ruing Movement for Multi-party
Democracy (MMD) against tribalism.
</P>
<P>
Sunday Mail today quoted the president as saying that there is no room
for campaigning on tribal lines and that any one found doing so
will be severely disciplined.
</P>
<P>
He issued the warning Saturday when he opened the MMD provincial
conference in Ndola, in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba told the candidates not to insult each other in their
campaigns but to explain to the people what they would be able to
do once elected.
</P>
<P>
"Do not approach elections on tribal lines. You should elect
people on merit and those that would run the party effectively,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that he will not tolerate any one who would
start campaigning for the MMD presidency for the year 2001,
saying such people were undermining his authority because he is
still the president.
</P>
<P>
He said campaigning for the MMD presidency will only be
allowed in the year 2001 and not now.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the adoption of councillors in the forthcoming
local government elections, Chiluba said that the party will not
adopt any member who already has a party position because this
has in the past worked to the detriment of the party. 
</P>
