<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Sign Of Swans On China's "Swan Lake" This Winter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Winter is here, but there's not
a swan in sight on the lakes of the southern part of Shanxi
province.
</P>
<P>
Not a single swan has landed at the nature reserve near
Yuncheng city, which has four lakes on a 4,800-hectare area of
wetlands, even though other migratory wildfowl like egrets, gulls,
and ducks can been seen. It was a major stopover in the past of
swans migrating from Siberia from mid-October to mid-November.
The birds used to number 500 or 600 at one time, local officials
say.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that swans are more cold-resistant than some other
migratory birds and their delayed appearance may be the result of
the El Nino effect that has caused a rise in temperatures in the
Northern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi Province has also suffered from drought this winter
because of less rainfall, causing drying up of some of the
wetlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
