<HEADLINE> 22 Foreign Missions to Observe Poll in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Twentytwo foreign missions
have been cleared by Kenya's Electoral Commission (EC) to observe
the country's second multi-party general elections set for
December 29, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign monitors will also observe the parliamentary
nominations to be held in the constituencies Monday and Tuesday,
EC Chairman Samuel Kivuitu was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Kivuitu called on all EC officers to facilitate a
conducive environment to enable the diplomats to observe the
elections peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The missions are from the U.S., Britain, Germany,
Canada, Denmark, Austria, Spain, Finland, Poland, Netherlands,
Indonesia, Greece, Belgium, Australia, Sweden, Ethiopia, Czech,
Italy, Norway, Japan, Hungary and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
A total of 15 candidates have been cleared to run for the
Kenyan presidency in the December 29 elections, the most crowded
presidential race since the country declared independence in
early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, 74 and in power
for 19 years, is widely expected to win the campaign with
five-year more tenure largely due to the division of the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
His powerful rivals include Mwai Kibaki of Democratic Party of
Kenya, Wamalwa Kijana of FORD-Kenya, Raila Odinga of National
Development Pary of Kenya, Charity Ngilu of Social Democratic
Party and Martin Shikuku of FORD-Asili.
</P>
<P>
A presidential aspirant can be qualified as he (she) gets the
mandatory 1,000 signatures of supporters, but to be a legal
Kenyan president needs no less than 25 percent votes in five out
of the country's eight provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
