<HEADLINE> Thai Industry Restructuring Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's National Science and
Technology Committee has urged the government to increase
competence in technology and restructure the export industries to
better compete in the global market.
</P>
<P>
The committee, chaired by Science, Technology and Environment
Minister Yingphan Manasikarn, said in a report that the government
should stress the role of science and technology in industries,
which will help tackle the economic problems facing the country.
</P>
<P>
It proposes allocation of 15 billion baht (357 million U.S.
dollars) into a fund for developing industrial competence and
export business. The money can come from loans from the World Bank
and the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be used to develop technology for potential
industries which will be fundamental in developing manufacturing
processes, management and marketing, the Bangkok Post reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The committee agreed that the country is lacking its own
technology for industries of both manufacturing and service
business which could sustain economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yongyuth Yuthawong, director of the National Science
and Technology Development Agency, said on Saturday that
technology upgrading should be the main factor in the country's
industry restructuring.
</P>
<P>
He said spending money in fighting the financial crisis alone
is not enough for the country in the long run, adding that an
amount of money should be put to support technology and research
in order to increase industrial competence in the global market.
</P>
</TEXT>
