<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Asian Meeting on Rehabilitation Network Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The second South Asian Conference
on the Community-Based Rehabilitation (CBR) Network has ended here
after issuing a declaration urging the region's governments and
NGOs to develop access to basic rehabilitation services to the
disabled by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Dhaka Declaration was adopted at the end of the conference
on Saturday. The four-day meeting began on December 3.
</P>
<P>
All the governments and NGOs in the region recognize that
handicap and disability are development issues, the declaration
said.
</P>
<P>
It stressed the need for cooperation among the governments and
NGOs in developing a systematic and planned approach for the
implementation of CBR to combat "ignorance, fear and superstition"
at all levels.
</P>
<P>
It suggested launching a national plan of action for community
level interventions by government and NGOs and said government
policies must be integrated into existing legislation and
implemented at the community level.
</P>
<P>
The declaration also suggested that assistance be given to
children with disabilities through early intervention programs.
</P>
<P>
Specialized rehabilitation support services for community
activities must be developed in conjunction with relevant
community level interventions, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
