<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepalese Children Administered Polio Vaccines Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 3.6 million Nepalese
children under the age of five will be administered polio vaccines
today under the country's second immunization program.
</P>
<P>
A total of 22,000 immunization centers have been set up with
some 100,000 volunteers involved in the program, Nepali newspapers
said.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government, the British and Norwegian governments
and some international organizations have provided vaccines and
other assistance worth 1.58 million U.S. dollars, the papers said.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government has declared December 7 this year and
January 18 next year as National Immunization Days as decided by
all the seven South Asian countries at the May summit held in
Male, the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
The first national immunization program was launched last year
with some 3.7 million children vaccinated against poliomyelitis.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is the only country in the world after Yemen which has
yet to complete the polio immunization.
</P>
<P>
The government has pledged to eradicate polio by 2000 as called
upon by the World Health Organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
