<HEADLINE> India's Congress Will Not Play Second Fiddle Any More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 7 (Xinhua)-- In order to enthuse its rank
and file, India's Congress Party has unveiled a new approach in
the run-up to the general elections and decided not to play second
fiddle to the United Front (UF) any more.
</P>
<P>
In the past 18 months, the Congress has been the main helper of
the UF for its rule in the central government.
</P>
<P>
Casting away its 18-month-old image as a secondary partner of
the UF, the Congress, in a statement issued on Saturday, attacked
the performance of the UF government and asserted the Congress'
primacy as the natural leader of the "secular" formation in the
fight against the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), labeled as the
"communal force" in India.
</P>
<P>
The Congress has ruled out national level alliance with the UF
in election campaigns. But it added that it would have some
cooperation with some of the UF constituents.
</P>
<P>
"Without the Congress support, the UF could not muster the
majority in the House and even if the Congress remained neutral,
it could not get more members than that of the BJP combination,"
the Congress statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Congress also blamed the current economic crisis including
the devaluation of the rupee on the UF government's inept handling
of the economy and inefficient management.  
</P>
</TEXT>
