<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5,000 More to Lose Jobs in Suspended Finance Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 5,000 more employees
working for Thailand's 58 suspended finance companies are expected
to lose their jobs starting Monday.
</P>
<P>
Since the suspension orders were given to the 58 firms by the
former administration in June and August, about 10,000 employees
have already been laid off.
</P>
<P>
The financial restructuring agency (FRA) will on Monday
announce which of the 58 suspended finance companies will be
allowed to reopen.
</P>
<P>
Finance sector sources believe the number will not be more than
five, possibly just three.
</P>
<P>
FRA chief, Tawatchai Yongkittikul, revealed on Saturday that
only about 1,000 finance staff will keep their jobs after Monday's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Those who will keep their jobs will help the FRA to chase
debts.
</P>
<P>
Finance companies allowed to reopen are expected to be able to
resume operations within two weeks. However, the FRA will allow
them two to three months to find new partners to boost their
capital.
</P>
<P>
As for those companies which have failed the FRA's screening
and will have to be closed, their accounts will be audited to see
if dishonest management has been involved in their operations.
</P>
<P>
Private firms have been hired to help the FRA split good from
bad debts, according to deputy finance minister Pichet
Phanvichartkul Saturday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Tourism Shadowed by Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Travel agents and hotel
managers are concerned that the economic and currency upheaval in
Asia is causing less visitors travelling across Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The number of Asians visiting Southern California leaped 21
percent last year to 2.4 million, but industry officials believe
that number could drop significantly this year as a result of
economic turmoil in Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Thailand and
Indonesia. They predict Southern California tourism to grow no
more than 2 percent to 3 percent in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
"It will be expensive for the people of those countries to
travel to the United States," said Jack Kyser, chief economist for
the Los Angeles Economic Development Corp., in a speech at the
Southern California Visitor Industry Outlook conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the number of U.S. visitors to Asia, though
also decreasing, has not been as severe, partly because U.S.-based
travelers still benefit from the dollar's strength against the
weakening Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
"The hotel prices in Asia are down and air fares are under
pressure," said Scott Mowrer, U.S. sales manager for Cathay
Pacific Airways of Hong Kong, "It is a pretty good time to be
shopping for bargains to and from Asia."
</P>
<P>
Cathay is among the Asian-based carriers that are
hurting. Others include Japan Airlines, Korean Air, Singapore
Airlines and Malaysian Airlines.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. carriers suffering the most are Northwest Airlines and
United Airlines which dominate U.S. airlines serving the region.
</P>
<P>
Declines have been particularly evident in the number of Asian
tourists visiting Hawaii and the mainland United States, where Los
Angeles and San Francisco are gateway stops.
</P>
<P>
Travel agents and hotel managers believe that Southern
California would have to work harder at making overseas visitors
comfortable if it was to avoid a fall-off.
</P>
<P>
They suggested that hoteliers to hire more Asian-speaking
employees to woo limited Asian tourists and to offer discounts or
room rates, currently averaging to 106.9 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
