<HEADLINE> Speculatives Turn Weak on BSE Market Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 7 (Xinhua)-- Speculatives turned weak and
the sensitive index fell 91.21 points in dull trade on the Bombay
Stock Exchange (BSE) market last week following heavy selling
pressure by operators disappointed at parliament dissolution and
the mid-term poll announcement.
</P>
<P>
Failure of political parties to find a solution to form a
government, which led to dissolution of Parliament and the
announcement of elections, made traders nervous as the whole
process is likely to have an adverse effect on the economy.
</P>
<P>
The market situation would have been worse if financial
institutions had not extended their support that was termed by the
marketmen as aggressive at the fag end. The rupee's plunge to an
all-time low of 39.90/95 against the U.S. dollar during the
trading on last Tuesday also affected the sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index showed a fall of 91.21 points, ending
the week at 3,469.08 as against the previous weekend close of
3,560.29. The national index lost substantially from the previous
weekend close of 1,543.10 to close the week at 1,504.38, recording
a loss of 38.72 points.  
</P>
</TEXT>
