<HEADLINE> Russia Urges for Unified Legal System Within CIS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Moscow, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia urged for a unified legal
system within CIS to boost cooperation among its members,
according to ITAR-TASS.
</P>
<P>
Yegor Stroyev, Chairman of the Russian Federal Assembly and of
CIS Interparliamentary Conference expressed this at the 10th
meeting of Interparliamentary Conference of CIS (Commonwealth of
Independent States) in St. Petersburg Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Stroyev said the Conference has enacted more
than 50 laws including the criminal law, code of criminal
procedures and the civil law as well as legal documents on
financial offenses since its founding five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he added, the organization has also took part in the
peace keeping activities on "hot spots" within the CIS borders and
has established extensive relations with parliamentary
organizations of the European Council and the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Legislative leaders from Azerbaijan, Armenia, Belarus, Georgia,
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Russia and Tajikistan attended
the meeting while Ukraine sent in observers.
</P>
<P>
A new package of legal documents on banking, finance, education,
ecology and charity and an appeal to the UN Assembly and other
international organizations to stop the information war were
passed on Saturday's meeting, ITAR-TASS said. 
</P>
