<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Trade With South Africa to Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Vast trade and investment
opportunities will open up for China and South Africa after
diplomatic relations are established, today's China Daily has
reported.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela has promised to forge
diplomatic ties with China before the end of this year, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Foreign Ministry has confirmed that Vice-Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen will fly to South Africa later
this month to sign a communique on the establishment of diplomatic
relations, it said.
</P>
<P>
"We expect Sino-South African trade to reach 1.6 billion
US dollars by the end of this year," said Shi Guangsheng,
vice-minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese customs, bilateral trade volume in the
first 10 months of this year grew 15.3 percent to 1.25 billion US
dollars. China's imports from South Africa were valued at 600
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to South Africa early in November, a Chinese
trade delegation led by Shi signed business contracts and letters
of intent with its South African counterpart worth 630 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
China will set up a number of projects to develop natural
resources in South Africa, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
China may also establish textiles and electronics projects as
well as CKD (complete knockdown) or SKD (semi-knockdown) projects
there.
</P>
<P>
Shi said bilateral capital and technical co-operation could
even cover mining, agriculture telecommunications and power
sectors.
</P>
<P>
China's trade with Africa as a whole reached 4.52 billion US
dollars in the first ten months of this year, up 41 percent over
the same period of last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He estimated trade with Africa for the whole of 1997 will
reach 5.5 billion US dollars to 6 billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
