<HEADLINE> China to Burn 1.48 Billion Tons of Coal by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to burn a
total of 1.48 billion tons of coal by the year of 2000 to fuel its
express economic growth, an official source said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic consumers will use 1.43 billion tons of coal, with the
remaining 50 million tons exported, today's China Daily reported,
quoting Li Hongxun, deputy director of the Transportation and
Energy Department of the State Planning Commission, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The largest coal-consuming industries include the power
generating and heat-supplying industries, 600 million tons; the
light industry, 135 million tons; and the metallurgical industry,
125 million tons.
</P>
<P>
China's coal resources are mainly located in the northwestern
and Southwestern areas, where the economies are not as developed
as those in the coastal regions, so coal has to be transported
from the west to east.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, 382 million tons of coal in Shanxi,
Shaanxi and western Inner Mongolian Autonomous Region will be
transported to cities in East and Northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Li said that construction of new coal mines will concentrate on
eastern and central China to provide sufficient fuel for the
development of the local economies.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 and 1997, the central government put a total of 37
billion yuan (about 4.45 billion US dollars) into construction for
the coal industries, increasing its production capacity by 63
million tons.
</P>
<P>
"In 1998, coal supplying conditions will be good and coal
production and transportation will meet the requirements of
national economic development," Li said.
</P>
<P>
China's coal reserves are estimated at more than 1,000 billion
tons. This year China is expected to produce 1.42 billion tons of
coal. Coal accounts for 75 percent of China's energy needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
