<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Currency Stability Promised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese yuan will remain
stable despite pressure on the country's exports arising from the
recent devaluation of several Southeast Asian currencies, today's
China Daily has reported.
</P>
<P>
The Renminbi would suffer neigher sharp devaluation nor strong
appreciation at least in the first two quarters of next year said
Tao Liming, director of the Institute of International Finance of
the Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
He said that the upheaval that hit the Southeast Asian
countries will not result in any direct impact on the Chinese yuan
as China has not released its foreign exchange controls over
capital accounts.
</P>
<P>
He said enterprises producing textiles, shoes, household
electric appliances and garments will face tougher challenges as
these products are the main export products of the Southeast Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Other Chinese export products including machinery, ships,
automobiles and crude oil will not be influenced as Southeast
Asian countries seldom export these kinds of goods, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese currency, would be buoyed by other macroeconomic
factors including higher State foreign exchange reserves and
continuous inflows of overseas capital, Tao said.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors and domestic individuals have become more
sensitive to the fluctuations of the Renminbi in the wake of the
Southeast Asian financial crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Renminbi stability will enhance the confidence of overseas
investors and traders while providing support for the stability of
the Hong Kong dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
