<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Should Bow to Market in Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- While mergers and acquisitions
are all the rage in China, government must bow to the dictates of
the market in order to ward off "unhappy and senseless marriages,"
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Recently, a string of government-led mergers aimed at creating
corporate giants to do battle with mounting foreign competition
have begun to break the shackles of the vested interests of
various ministries, regions and other enterprise-owners in China.
</P>
<P>
The government administrations had to loosen their grip on the
management and operation of State enterprises, said Jiang Hong, a
researcher with the National Administrative Bureau of State-owned
Property.
</P>
<P>
"The government is not supposed to be in a position to directly
handle their business activities because its limited access to
ever-changing information about technology and markets affects its
decision-making capability," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He blamed some local governments for interfering with the
process of mergers that transcend the restrictive limits of
regions and ownerships.
</P>
<P>
"Pursuit of profits and market share expansion should become
mergers," Jiang said, noting that administrative interference
might cause distortion of the economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Besides the prevention of unnecessary government-organized
mergers and acquisitions, Li Baomin, deputy director of the
Department of the Production System under the State Commission for
Restructuring Economic Systems, underscored the evaluation and
management of State-owned assets in the process of asset shake-up.
</P>
<P>
A lack of concrete measures has constituted a barrier to the
ongoing reform of State-owned enterprises, although a set of laws
and regulations are being drawn up, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
Executive managerial personnel should be selected according to
their performance, and based on the market principle of "survival
of the fittest", Jiang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
