<DOCNO> XIE19971207.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in China Expected to Grow in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese officials and
researchers agree that more foreign capital will flow into China
in the coming year, though potential investors have been waiting
to see whether China would be another domino to fall in the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Next year will witness more foreign capital inflow," today's
China's Daily quoted Zhang Shangtang, vice-chairman of the
China Assn of Enterprises With Foreign Investment, as saying.
</P>
<P>
China expects to be the world's second largest recipient of
foreign investment for the fifth consecutive year in 1997,
according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that actual foreign investment in
China during the first ten months of this year reached 41.93
billion US dollars, a surge of 26.86 percent year-on-year, though
contractual investment dropped 28.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Buy-outs, mergers, acquisitions, and auctions of shares of State
firms, which were officially endorseed by the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China in September, will offer
unprecedented opportunities to foreign investors, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Min, chairman of the Beijing-based Sinotrust, a major risk
management company, said that China still has a lower credit risk
rating than some Southeast Asian countries and till now most
foreign investors are satisfied with China's business credit.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhao said that China should have a more transparent
information system to help foreign investors analyze credit risks,
as risk analyses are becoming increasingly popular as China opens
its markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
