<HEADLINE> Beijing Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Central China's Hunan Province has over the recent three
years attached keen importance to the buildup of infrastructure,
which has in turn sent the provincial economy onto a track of
rapid development.
</P>
<P>
Hunan's provincial gross domestic product grew at an average
of 11.9 percent between 1994 and 1996, 5.4 percentage points
higher than the average growth rate for the five years prior to
1994. In the first half of this year Hunan's GDP expanded by 12.1
percent year-on-year, 2.6 percentage points higher than the
national average.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng sent a massage of congratulations to the
establishment of the China Harbor Engineering Group, which has
17.2 billion yuan of assets and employs about 800,000 people. The
Group has been on the list of Top 225 International Contractors of
the US magazine of "Engineering News Record" since 1992.
</P>
<P>
-- Hu Jintao, a senior official of the Communist Party of
China, urged the nation's trade unions to make greater efforts to
arouse worker's enthusiasm for continued reforms in state-run
enterprises, thereby helping to fulfill the tasks set forth by the
15th National Congress of CPC convened in September this year.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The grain output of east China's Jiangsu Province is
expected to break the hallmark of 35 billion kg for the first time
this year. Jiangsu's annual grain output beat the marks of 25
billion kg and 30 billion kg in 1979 and 1983, respectively.
</P>
<P>
-- Ningbo, a port city in east China's Zhejiang Province, has
in the past two years effectively carried out a program to make
its enterprises more competitive. The program focuses on
developing enterprise groups and shifting the economic growth
mode.
</P>
<P>
-- China's law enforcement departments will launch a
comprehensive crackdown on the manufacturing and trading of fake
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Vast trade and investment opportunities will open up for
China and South Africa after the two countries establish
diplomatic relations later this month. Shi Guangsheng,
vice-minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said that
trade between China and South Africa will reach 1.6 billion US
dollars by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
-- Officials and researchers agree that the approaching Year of
the Tiger is likely to bring further waves of foreign capital into
China, although potential investors have been waiting to see
whether the country would be another domino to fall in the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
-- A noted financial expert of the Institute of International
Finance of the Bank of China said that the Chinese yuan will
remain stable despite pressure on the country's exports arising
from the recent devaluation of currencies of several Southeast
Asian nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
